Exercise 8 - Physically based rendering (PBR)

Learning objectives

In this exercise we will learn the basics of the implementation of a physically-based material.

  • How to enforce energy conservation in the shader.
  • The different parts of the Cook-Torrance equation for specular.
  • The differences between dielectric and metallic materials.
References
  • LearnOpenGL - PBR - Lighting: https://learnopengl.com/PBR/Lighting
  • Physically Based Rendering in Filament: https://google.github.io/filament/Filament.html
  • Marmoset - Basic Theory of Physically-Based Rendering: https://marmoset.co/posts/basic-theory-of-physically-based-rendering/
Initial implementation

Once more, we continue with the car from previous exercises.

Building on what we had, I have added some improvements:

  • Changed the framebuffer and the albedo textures to sRGB gamma space.
  • The first light is a directional light. Instead of changing the position, we can use the UI to change the direction. On the shader side, we are testing if lightRadius is 0 to know if it is directional.
  • We are using normal map textures.
  • There is a skybox as the background.
  • I added some subtle environment reflection to the car.

As always, take some time to get familiar with the C++ code used for this new features.

Apart from the directional light, in this scene we have a second light moving in circles, to see how our material reacts with dynamically. You can use the UI to modify both lights and the car paint material.

You may have noticed that we have 3 separate blocks in the material. The color property is common to Blinn-Phong and PBR shaders, but the other properties are specific to each shader.
Exercise 8.1
 Shadow map

Before we start modifying the lighting equation, there is something important still missing in this scene: Shadows. We are going to add a shadow map to the directional light.

There are a few steps required for shadow mapping:

  • Create the shadow map texture (We have done this for you already, find it in C++ code).
  • During the main loop, fill the shadow map by rendering the objects with a specific shader, using the texture as framebuffer (We have done this for you already, find it in C++ code).
  • When rendering the scene, set the shadow uniforms (shadow map and light matrix) in the objects shaders. (We have done this for you already, find it in C++ code).
  • In the vertex shader, obtain the position of the vertex in light space, and pass it to the fragment shader. You can use the lightSpaceMatrix to transform from world space to light space.
  • In the fragment shader, you need to read the depth from the shadow map and compare it to the depth of the current fragment in light space. Fill in the function GetShadow() following the instructions in the comments.

Ok, now you should be seeing something resembling a shadow, but there are 2 problems that we need to fix:

  • There is a large area in shadow far from the light:
    The reason for this is that the depth of the current fragment at some point gets bigger than -1 (the minimum value in the shadow map), leading it to believe that it is in shadow. The easiest fix for this is to clamp the Z component of the shadow map space position to a (-1, 1) range.
  • The surface of the objects suffers from shadow acne:
    As we explained during a previous lecture, this is fixed by adding a bias to the depth value that we read from the texture. In this case you can simply add a fixed small value (0.01) to the depth.

Nice looking shadow! Don't forget to copy the fragment shader changes to pbr_shading.frag.
Exercise 8.2
Ambient

From this exercise on, we will be working on pbr_shading.frag only.

Adding a constant color as the value of ambient light does not really follow PBR constraints. Is there something we can do to improve it?

Let's take advantage of the environment map, that represent the light of the surrounding objects. Replace the ambient calculation using these steps:

  • Sample the environment map in the normal direction. This will give us the amount of light coming from that direction. Since we are looking for an average of the light, we should sample a high mipmap (> 5). You can specify which mipmap to sample using textureLod instead of texture. You will need to pass the normal to the GetAmbientLighting() function
    Ideally the mipmaps of this texture would have been preprocessed to store the right amount of light that we are looking for, but the automatic mipmaps give also an ok result.
  • That light will be reflected by our surface in all directions after absorbing some light, so we need to multiply it by albedo and divide it by PI. There are no magic numbers now, this is the amount of ambient that we receive, instead of ambientReflectance.
  • We can keep ambient occlusion, it does not add more energy.

The scene looks slightly darker now because the default ambient value was a bit too high. We lost the ability to tune the ambient reflectance, but, on the other hand, if we changed our environment map the car will integrate better with the new lighting automatically.
Exercise 8.3
Energy conservation

One of the key points of PBR is energy conservation. For Blinn-Phong shading we balanced the amount of diffuse and specular light individually and then added them together. In PBR, this two magnitudes are connected. Light will either get directly reflected as specular or scattered in all directions as diffuse. Therefore, for 1 unit of light energy, there will be 1 or less (because of absorption) units split between diffuse and specular.

Let's work on that:

  • For specular light we will not do anything yet, even though the Blinn-Phong formula is not PBR. We will take care of that in the next part.
  • For diffuse, the energy reflected in this way gets evenly distributed in all directions. The value needs to be divided by PI.
  • If you try it now, you will see that the image is way darker than before. This is because it was wrong before and we adjusted the light intensity to that setup. To fix this, go to C++ code, find where we set the light uniforms, and multiply the light energy by PI (only if we are using pbr_shading.frag).
  • Now we just need to make sure that the ratio of diffuse and specular light adds to 1. You can use the function mix to blend between specular and diffuse. We still don't know what we should use as blend factor, so for now we will just use the roughness, which is already in range (0, 1).

After this change the specular light will be too bright. You can divide it (incorrectly) by PI for now to get the same result we had before, on just continue to the next exercises where we will take care of that properly.
Exercise 8.4
Cook-Torrance: Fresnel term

In the previous exercise we discussed how the light will be split between diffuse and specular. The fresnel term is the one that determines the ratio of these.

For this exercise we will use the Schlick approximation to Fresnel presented in the lecture.

  • Implement the Fresnel Schlick approximation in FresnelSchlick().
  • In the main function, get the value of the fresnel for the light, using the provided F0 value and the cosine of the angle between the half vector and the view vector (clamped to positive values). Use that value to replace the roughness in the mix between diffuse and specular.
    Beware, the order of diffuse and specular will be different now: full diffuse when Fresnel is 0, full specular when Fresnel is 1.
  • We can do the same for indirect lighting. We can mix between ambient (diffuse indirect) and environment reflection(specular indirect). In this case, the Fresnel value will be computed using F0 and the angle between the normal and the view vector (clamped to positive values)

One thing worth mentioning here is that the format used for this g-buffer (RG16F) can take negative values, that is why we don't need to transform it to a [0, 1] range. Therefore the normal don't look blueish like in the normal maps.
Exercise 8.5
Cook-Torrance: Distribution function

Now it is time to change the way we compute specular.

We will replace the Blinn-Phong model with a specular based on Cook-Torrance equation:

  • In main(), replace the call to GetBlinnPhongSpecularLighting() with a call to the GetCookTorranceSpecularLighting() function.
    This function is already implemented, but some of the functions that it is using are empty.
  • Implement the normal distribution function using the GGX distribution. You just have to implement the formula in DistributionGGX().

This new specular is finally physically-based!

There are some areas that are too bright now. Don't worry about that, this is because we still need to complete the geometry term of the equation, that accounts for light that gets blocked with roughness.
Exercise 8.6
Cook-Torrance: Geometry term

The final part of the Cook-Torrance equation is the geometry term (also known as visibility term).

As we discussed in the lecture, we can split this equation in 2 symmetric parts: one for the incoming light (shadowing) and one for the outgoing light (masking).

  • Implement the geometry term using the GeometrySmith() function, using GeometrySchlickGGX() 2 times, one for incoming light (L) and one for outgoing light (V).
  • Implement the formula for partial visibility in GeometrySchlickGGX().

Congratulations! Our renderer is now PBR... for dielectric materials.
Exercise 8.7
 Metallic materials

There is a last part for today's exercise. It is easy and quite rewarding, so please give it a try!

We saw that metallic materials behave slightly different than dielectric. In particular, their specular is tinted instead of white.

We have added a uniform metalness to control how metallic is our material (0: dielectric, 1: metallic). Values in between are there for dirty metals, etc.

  • Implement the geometry term using the GeometrySmith() function, using GeometrySchlickGGX() 2 times, one for incoming light (L) and one for outgoing light (V).
  • Implement the formula for partial visibility in GeometrySchlickGGX().
